<h2>How to use this partner</h2>

<p>Bring a specific design decision you're weighing — not a general question about engineering. Tell the Coach what you're trying to accomplish, what your constraints are (budget, geography, deadline), and what choices you're considering. It will help you surface trade-offs, not pick for you.</p>

<p>Two prompts you can paste in to get started:</p>

<ul>
  <li><em>"I'm designing for Tokyo. I have $1.5M. Help me think through where to spend it."</em></li>
  <li><em>"My iteration #2 score dropped. I think it's because I moved hospitals inland. Walk me through what might have happened."</em></li>
</ul>

<h2>Opening message</h2>

<blockquote>"Hi — I'm the Engineering Coach. What are you working on? Walk me through what you're trying to accomplish and what constraints you're working with. Then we'll think through the decisions together."</blockquote>

<h2>Example exchange — what working looks like</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>You</th><th>The Engineering Coach</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr>
      <td>I'm designing for Tokyo. I have $1.5M and I'm trying to figure out where to spend it.</td>
      <td>Great. Before we talk budget, let's get the priorities clear. If you could only do ONE of these — save the maximum number of lives, keep critical infrastructure (hospitals, power) operational, or protect the most expensive buildings — which would you pick? There's no wrong answer, but you can't optimize for all three with $1.5M. What's your call?</td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Watch out for</h2>

<p>The Coach can drift into making suggestions that look like decisions ("I'd put the tsunami wall on tile A6"). Even when phrased as a suggestion, this teaches reliance on the AI rather than building your own engineering reasoning. If you catch it naming specific tiles or buildings, ask it to redirect: <em>"Don't tell me where — help me figure out the criteria I should use."</em></p>

<p>If you're confused about <em>why</em> something is a hazard (rather than what to do about it), use the <a href="/ai-partners/plate-tectonics-tutor/">Plate Tectonics Tutor</a> instead.</p>

<h2>Before you go — documentation</h2>

<p>At the end of a substantive conversation, the partner will remind you:</p>

<blockquote>"Before you go — note in your <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation</a>: what's one engineering trade-off we discussed that you're going to act on, and what's one I raised that you decided NOT to act on, with your reasoning?"</blockquote>

